Subject: Re: Crypto testing
Lines: 45

 
In article <CEuBFI.FpB@cix.compulink.co.uk>, Keith Lockstone (klockstone@cix.compulink.co.uk) writes:
>
>Many times on sci.crypt we see a message from a novice come up 
>saying 'here's my new SUPADOOPA_MK3 cipher what do you think of 
>it?'  Old timers sometimes say 'read the FAQ' and hopefully the 
>thread ends there. 
> 
>As an extension to the FAQ, may I suggest that a few conventions 
>are agreed upon and that certain FTP sites maintain a directory 
>of programs that can be used for analysis of crypto products.  
>Then, when the perennial question comes up, the tyro can be 
>referred to a set of tests that s/he should test their idea 
>against.
> 
>Amongst the conventions to be set up would be the source language 
>for the analysis programs (probably C) and an interchange file 
>format for files of random numbers, plaintext etc.
> 
>With regard to stream ciphers there is the need for a library of 
>programs for estimating the crypto-strength of pseudorandom 
>number sequences.  (Starting with Knuth's random number tests 
>from his book on Seminumerical Algorithms) 
> 
>Similarly there would be a need for programs to estimate the 
>strength of block ciphers - starting with a differential 
>cryptanalyser.
> 
>Advantages would include an improvement in the general level of 
>'crypto literacy' as well as improved crypto products in the 
>marketplace.  Successful ideas could be then aired on sci.crypt 
>are more subtle forms of cryptanalysis developed.
> 
>Comments anyone?
> 
>Best regards,
> 
>Keith Lockstone.
> 
>

_I'd_ certainly like to see something like this.

Dave Merriman


